NEW YORKERS & COMPANY
NEW YORKERS & COMPANY; What Did the C.E.O. Have for Breakfast?


By CONSTANCE L. HAYS


Published: September 4, 1994









                    LOTS of money managers have big corner offices high above midtown. But Laura J. Sloate may be the only one whose carpet is covered with dog hair.        

                    The shedding is the work of Quartz, her 19-month-old German shepherd, who is a finicky eater and her guide dog as of July. But the rest of the trappings -- the computers, the piles of research material, the elegant Eisenstadt photographs decorating one wall -- are the doing of Ms. Sloate. Though she has been blind since the age of 6, she has built up a successful firm that bears her name and manages $600 million in assets for wealthy individuals and institutional investors.        

                    "My personal philosophy is extreme conservatism, and she fits the bill," said Don Gruhn, who has held a seat on the New York Stock Exchange for 36 years and hired Ms. Sloate 17 years ago to manage several million dollars in accounts for him and his family. "There are a lot of gunslingers who do well in an up market and get destroyed in a down market," he says. "And Laura has never had bad, bad losses."        

                    Nothing, frankly, seems to get in her way. Her day begins at dawn with a run on 100 flights of stairs, up and down, in her Upper East Side apartment building. She has skimmed the headlines of eight newspapers by the time breakfast is over. She's fed the dog and bustled both of them into her chauffeured car to get to work by 8:30. Then it's 12 hours in the office, interrupted only to take Quartz for a walk around the block, often followed by dinner with one of her clients.        

                    She serves on half a dozen boards, both professional and philanthropic. In her spare time, she follows the National Football League on television (she's devoted to the New York Jets and the San Francisco 49ers), rides a tandem bicycle steered by members of the Columbia University men's track team, goes to the opera and museums and pursues interests like studying the Bible.        

                    "I have things to do 30 hours a day, and there's only 24," she says, not terribly lightly. "And I have to waste a certain amount of time sleeping."        

                    Her blindness, caused by detached retinas, is not something that she tends to dwell on. She has little patience for organizations that portray the blind as one more disadvantaged minority.        

                    "I really think that blind people are made a special category by society, and they want to be, because they can use it as an escape," she says. "But with a guide dog and some electronic equipment today, it's an equal playing field."        

                    Now 49, she chose a business renowned for its brutality, and she has been as tough as anyone else. At one point her nickname was Cobra. Last year, she had a falling-out with her brother, Martin, who had been a partner. She said they split over her decision to drop the firm's retail brokerage business, which she considered too small to justify the liability involved. They haven't spoken much since then.        

                    "I'm a perfectionist," Ms. Sloate says, "and I guess I'm pretty driven. I'm pretty tough on myself, too. But what is that saying? The person who loses well isn't really a winner?"        

                    Clients quickly learn not to suggest investments to her. She runs the show.        

                    "We feel she is extremely knowledgeable about the companies she looks at to invest in," said Brian K. Lavery, a senior financial analyst with Geo-Centers, a Newton, Mass.-based defense contractor who calls Ms. Sloate the most profitable of five money managers running the company's profit-sharing retirement plan. "She can tell you what the C.E.O. had for breakfast."        

                    Has she ever lost out because people didn't trust a blind person to manage their money? "I think so," she says. "Nobody's ever going to admit it. But I'm sure other people lose business because someone didn't like their personality, or didn't like their shirt."        

                    To accommodate her lack of eyesight, her office is equipped with a talking computer that chants the ticker tape in a fairly human sounding voice, and a digitalizer, which converts printed matter to computerspeak. Students tape-record more reading material, which she listens to day and night, and others who go over the newspapers with her every evening. She studies all this information to detect events and trends that might push prices up or down.        

                    "We can only guesstimate educationally and hope we're right," Ms. Sloate said.        

                    Sitting back in an upholstered leather chair, she has a certain raw-boned charm, and within minutes her supremely confident investing strategy has captured center stage. She likes drugstore chains at the moment.        

                    "These chains have become the delivery agent of the prescription benefit program," Ms. Sloate says.        

                    Then she rattles off reasons she expects their value to spiral upward: aging baby boomers will need more prescription drugs, especially as hospitals send people home earlier than they used to, and will buy them from the corner drugstore for the convenience.        

                    She has picked some winners in her time -- 24 in a row, at one point, which earned admiration from her peers -- and some losers, too. There was Avis, which she liked but which sank to $5 a share from $30, she says, in the 1970's after she recommended it to investors.        

                    In many ways, New York is uniquely accommodating to her life style. In snowstorms, she is able to board the Fifth Avenue bus for the trip downtown. "I wouldn't be able to do that in Los Angeles," she says.  She dines at restaurants like Coco Pazzo and Girasole, Quartz watching the world go by from beneath her table.        

                    "I ice skate, too," she says. "I could probably Rollerblade, but I've never tried it. I used to play basketball. I memorized where the basket was, and I sank 35 to 40 percent of my shots."        

                    She started out as a clerk in 1966, working for a mutual fund that folded a few months later. It was meant to be a one-time thing, a break from doctoral studies in American history at Columbia, but Ms. Sloate was hooked.        

                    She moved along to series of jobs, and then in 1974 with a friend, Neil Weisman, who had grown disenchanted with being a cog in a big firm, she began Sloate, Weisman, Murray & Company Mr. Weisman left the company on good terms in 1986.        

                    The point of her work, Ms. Sloate says, is to make money for her clients, although she makes plenty of it herself (she would not divulge her salary). She has set up a foundation, Hermione, that makes grants to causes like education and AIDS. "We did six figures this year," she says.        

                    "At a very early stage, you think your intelligence and success mean something," she said. "Over time, you find it doesn't mean that much. There are lots of other things in life."        

                    Photo: Laura Sloate has been hooked on investing since 1966. Her guide dog, Quartz, is new to 12-hour days at the office. (Catrina Genovese for The New York Times)        








 


















 
















































 

